#
# Kid-SCII : a fun extended ASCII character map
# (C) 2016 Woldrich, Inc.
#
# I'm basing this character set off of IBM Extended ASCII  http://www.tacktech.com/display.cfm?ttid=27
#
# I get symbol name cues from Wikipedia, http://www.theasciicode.com.ar/, and
# http://ascii-table.com/ascii-extended-pc-list.php
#
# As a general rule, anywhere I find a control code in the ascii table, I replace it with an interesting
# extended character from the Commodore 64 character set rather than taking the suggested character from the
# IBM PC character set.
#
# For characters above 127, I take cues from the IBM Extended Ascii character set with rare exceptions where
# other characters (or their inverts) would produce the same glyph.  For example, 219 and 255 can both be
# produced using space (32) either directly or through inversion.  219 and 255 are used in Kid-SCII for the
# checkmark and chunky checkerboard.
#
# The hope is that the IBM Extended ASCII combined with characters from Commodore will be suitable for making
# many simple games without having to resort to character redefinition.  For example, the four card suits are
# represented.  That, plus numbers, plus colors, plus square card outlines would be enough to make a card game.
#
# Below is the actual data for the character maps.
